Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Naomi Ayibaemi Frank-Opigo¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset that contains borrower data and loan data for 113937 loan listings in the USA.

#Changing data types
#Converting Listing Creation Date,Closed Date, First Recorded Credit Line and Loan Origination Date to datetime data
loan[['ListingCreationDate','ClosedDate','FirstRecordedCreditLine','LoanOriginationDate']]=loan[['ListingCreationDate','ClosedDate','FirstRecordedCreditLine','LoanOriginationDate']].apply(pd.to_datetime)

#Extracting year from listing creation  date into a separate column
loan['Year'] = loan['ListingCreationDate'].dt.year

#Extracting quarter from listing creation date into a separate column
loan['Quarter'] = loan['ListingCreationDate'].dt.quarter
In [4]:

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loan entries with 81 details each. The data types include : floats, integers,datetime, categorical, boolean and string. Most variables are numeric. The following variables have fixed categories or ranges:

  1. Prosper rating (numeric) : 0 - N/A, 1 - HR, 2 - E, 3 - D, 4 - C, 5 - B, 6 - A, 7 - AA.
  2. Prosper rating(alpha) : AA -HR
  3. Prosper score : 1-10 (10 = lowest risk, 1 = highest risk), above 10 others are stated as 11
  4. Listing category: 0 - Not Available, 1 - Debt Consolidation, 2 - Home Improvement, 3 - Business, 4 - Personal Loan, 5 - Student Use, 6 - Auto, 7- Other, 8 - Baby&Adoption, 9 - Boat, 10 - Cosmetic Procedure, 11 - Engagement Ring, 12 - Green Loans, 13 - Household Expenses, 14 - Large Purchases, 15 - Medical/Dental, 16 - Motorcycle, 17 - RV, 18 - Taxes, 19 - Vacation, 20 - Wedding Loans
  5. Debt to income ratio : values above 1000% are indicated by 1001%

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in looking at the original loan amount. I want to explore how variables such as Home ownership,Listing category Prosper score, Occupations, regions, income range, time and other relate to the original loan amount given to loan seekers.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Original loan amount
  • Home Ownership
  • Income range
  • Prosper score
  • Investors
  • Borrower APR
  • Listing Category
  • Employment Status
  • Lender Yield
  • Borrower state
  • Listing Creation Date

Univariate Exploration¶

I will first explore the main variable of interest - Original loan amount

U.Fig-1 : What's the distribution of Original Loan amount ?¶

In [9]:
#Defining the theme color to be used for visualisations
colour = sb.color_palette()[2]

#a histigram of Original Loan amount
sb.histplot( loan['LoanOriginalAmount'], bins= 20, kde= False, color= colour)

#Setting plot labels & title
plt.xlabel('Original Loan Amount')
plt.ylabel('Borrower count')
plt.title('The Distribution of Loan Amount');

Observation¶

This is the main variable of interest. The graph shows a generalized decrease in number of loans as the loan amount increases except for odd peaks at 10,000 -15,000. The loan amount with the highest borrower count is 4,000 USD

Next up is the homeowner status, a boolean variable that is easy to asses. Home ownership makes for easy access to loan collateral and may therefore have significant effect on a borrower's loan seeking behaviour

U.Fig-2 : Are more borrowers home owners?¶

In [10]:
#countplot of Homeowners and Non-Homeowners
sb.countplot ( data = loan, x = 'IsBorrowerHomeowner', color = colour)

#Rotating x-xis ticks for visibility and setting plot title
plt.xticks (rotation=50)
plt.ylabel('Borrower count')
plt.title('Number of Non-Homeowner and Homeowner borrowers');

Observation¶

A look at the homeowner statistics.Surprisingly, the distribution of loans between home-owners and non-homeowners is almost equal even though a slightly larger number of borrowers are homeowners.

Another major variable of interest is the borrower income range as it could possibly affect a borrower's tendency to seek loans as well as capacity to pay back loans

U.Fig-3 : Which income range takes out the most loans¶

Observation¶

Most borrowers are in the lower middle class to middle class income range. Fewer borrowers earn above 100,000+. Borrowers with earnings categorized as "Not displayed","1-24,999", "0" are few. Some borrowers indicate that they are not employed.

The next variable to be explored is the prosper score. This ranges from 1 - 10 with 10 being low risk borrowe and 1 being a high risk borrower. The prosper score could potentially determine the confidence the lender institution has in a borrower and whether or not a borrower recieves approval for a loan

U.Fig-4 : What prosper scores have the largest number of loans¶

The prosper score shows a normal distributionwith the highest peaks falling between 4.0 and 8.0

A high number of investors a borrower has is expected to inspire confidence in lender institutions. It is assumed then that borrowers will seek to draw investors before applying for loans

U.Fig-5 : Are borrowers with more investors more likely to get loans?¶

In [13]:

#Setting y-axis label & plot title

Observation¶

There's an initial spike after which the graph shows a consistent decline indicating that a large number of borrowers have few, if any, investors. Very few form the exception having at least over 200 investors.This result is contrary to the original assumption as it shows that borrowers do not place a high value on garnering investors before applying for loans

Next up, the employment status of borrowers is explored. This is also a key variable as a steady source of income can play a role in determining the borrower's prosper score. Stable income can also allow borrower's to be confident in seeking out high loan amounts.

Considering the main variable of interest is the Original loan amount, it is also interesting to look at the variable up next. The borrower APR is essentially the annual interest rate.

The next variable - Lender Yield - indicates the lender's profit in a loan. The idea is that lender institutions factor in the profitability of a loan in their decision to disburse it.

Another significant portion of the borrower population in this category take out loans at 5000 USD, 10,000 USD and 15,000 USD with Borrower APRs spread through 0.1 - 0.4.

Also this group of borrowers begins to show outliers that seek loans above 30,000 USD. Borrowers with prosper scores of 9.0 also show a general reduction in interest rates as most borrowers have interest rates betwee 0.25 and minimums below 0.1
  • 10.0 and 11.0 These borrowers have the lowest risks. These borrowers seek loans ranging from as low as 1000 USD to the maximum possible amounts.They also have the lowest interest rates with maximum borrower APR generally aroun 0.25 and the minimum generally below 0.1
